tion (Yuma County, only), and 4) academic institution. Each is named in a box that also identifies the roles and responsibilities of each partner. The community health centers are responsible for program coordination, patient identification, health care access, and medical examinations. The local hospital is responsible for providing certified diabetes educators, diabetes training for promotores de salud, and individualized services. The Yuma County grassroots organization is responsible for providing the promotores de salud, community outreach, and case management. Arrows connect all three boxes, showing that each interacts with the other. The fourth box represents the academic institution, which is responsible for evaluation and technical assistance. Dotted lines connect the academic institution to each of the three other partners.","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":443,"renderedHeight":457,"naturalWidth":443,"naturalHeight":457,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"TOO_LONG","altReason":"alt text is 987 characters — consider a caption or description","bytes":12065},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2005/jan/www.cdc.gov/navimages/spacer.gif","alt":" ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":140,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":null,"naturalHeight":null,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"DECORATIVE","altReason":"alt=\"\" (decorative)","bytes":20905},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2005/jan/www.cdc.gov/navimages/spacer.gif","alt":" ","hasAlt":true,"isDecorative":false,"isMissingAlt":false,"ariaHidden":false,"rolePresentation":false,"renderedWidth":12,"renderedHeight":1,"naturalWidth":null,"naturalHeight":null,"loading":null,"decoding":null,"altVerdict":"DECORATIVE","altReason":"alt=\"\" (decorative)","bytes":20905},{"src":"https://www.cdc.gov/pcd/issues/2005/jan/www.cdc.gov/navimag